    }
}
```

}

Only a solid color on the screen.

I suggest modifying TextArea class as follows:

Add method:

```
public void setBottomAligned(boolean bottomAligned) {
   this.bottomAligned = bottomAligned;
}
```

Modify methods:

old method:

```
@Override
protected float getTextY (BitmapFont font, Drawable background) {
   float textY = getHeight();
   if (background != null) {
      textY = (int)(textY - background.getTopHeight());
   }
   return textY;
}
```

new method:

```
@Override
   protected float getTextY (BitmapFont font, Drawable background) {
      float textY;
      if (bottomAligned) {
         textY = getHeight();
         if (background != null) {
            textY = (int)(textY - background.getTopHeight());
         }
      } else {
         textY = font.getLineHeight();
         if (background != null) {
            textY = (int)(textY + background.getBottomHeight());
         }
      }
      return textY;
   }
```

old method:

```
@Override
   protected void drawText (Batch batch, BitmapFont font, float x, float y) {
      float offsetY = 0;
      for (int i = firstLineShowing * 2; i < (firstLineShowing + linesShowing) * 2 && i < linesBreak.size; i += 2) {
         font.draw(batch, displayText, x, y + offsetY, linesBreak.items[i], linesBreak.items[i + 1]);
         offsetY -= font.getLineHeight();
      }
   }
```

new method:

```
@Override
   protected void drawText (Batch batch, BitmapFont font, float x, float y) {
      float offsetY = 0;
      for (int i = firstLineShowing * 2; i < (firstLineShowing + linesShowing) * 2 && i < linesBreak.size; i += 2) {
         font.draw(batch, displayText, x, y + offsetY, linesBreak.items[i], linesBreak.items[i + 1]);
         if (bottomAligned)
            offsetY -= font.getLineHeight();
         else
            offsetY += font.getLineHeight();
      }
   }
```

Thanks!

Currently, the `com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx-platform` native libraries are only packaged as JARs. As a consequence, they do not incorporate well with the new Gradle build system.

A workaround exists in the current [`build.gradle`](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/blob/d8bcb5453946f8a6005397d3c612059073942880/extensions/gdx-setup/src/com/badlogic/gdx/setup/resources/android/build.gradle) template:

``` groovy
// needed to add JNI shared libraries to APK when compiling on CLI
tasks.withType(com.android.build.gradle.tasks.PackageApplication) { pkgTask ->
    pkgTask.jniFolders = new HashSet<File>()
    pkgTask.jniFolders.add(new File(projectDir, 'libs'))
}

// called every time gradle gets executed, takes the native dependencies of
// the natives configuration, and extracts them to the proper libs/ folders
// so they get packed with the APK.
task copyAndroidNatives() { 
    file("libs/armeabi/").mkdirs();
    file("libs/armeabi-v7a/").mkdirs();
    file("libs/x86/").mkdirs();

    configurations.natives.files.each { jar ->
        def outputDir = null
        if(jar.name.endsWith("natives-armeabi-v7a.jar")) outputDir = file("libs/armeabi-v7a")
        if(jar.name.endsWith("natives-armeabi.jar")) outputDir = file("libs/armeabi")
        if(jar.name.endsWith("natives-x86.jar")) outputDir = file("libs/x86")
        if(outputDir != null) {
            copy {
                from zipTree(jar)
                into outputDir
                include "*.so"
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Packaging them as [AARs](http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/aar-format) in addition to the current JARs would solve this problem and maintain backwards compatibility for non-Gradle builds.
